Class.terms:description: A social entity pertains to the interaction among individuals and groups.
Class.rdfs:label: social entity

Class.terms:description: A social structure is a social entity which consists of relationships between two or more entities.
Class.rdfs:label: social structure

Class.terms:description: An organization is a collective with a complex articulation of tasks, roles and responsibilities.
Class.rdfs:label: organization

Class.terms:description: A geographic position is the coordinate of an entity against some geographic coordinate system.
Class.rdfs:label: geographic position

Class.terms:description: information content entity is an object that requires some background knowledge or procedure to correctly interpret.
Class.rdfs:label: information content entity

Class.terms:description: A start date is a time instant pertaining to the date of the beginning of a process.
Class.rdfs:label: start date

Class.terms:description: An end date is a time instant pertaining to date of the end of a process.
Class.rdfs:label: end date

Class.terms:description: A spatial quantity is a quantity obtained from measuring the spatial extent of an entity
Class.rdfs:label: spatial quantity

Class.terms:description: A quantity that extends in single dimension.
Class.rdfs:label: 1D extent quantity

Class.terms:description: depth is the dimensional extent into a plane of a 3D projection of the object.
Class.rdfs:label: depth

Class.terms:description: height is the one dimensional extent along the vertical projection of a 3D object from a base plane of reference.
Class.rdfs:label: height

Class.terms:description: length is the longer dimensional extent along a 2D projection of the object.
Class.rdfs:label: length

Class.terms:description: width is the shorter dimensional extent perpendicular to a 2D projection of the object.
Class.rdfs:label: width

Class.terms:description: thickness is the shortest dimensional extent of a 3D projection of an object.
Class.rdfs:label: thickness

Class.terms:description: A quantity that extends in two dimensions.
Class.rdfs:label: 2D extent quantity

Class.terms:description: area is a quantity that pertains to the extent of a two-dimensional surface or shape, or planar lamina, in the plane.
Class.rdfs:label: area

Class.terms:description: A perimeter is a length of the outline that surrounds a two-dimensional shape.
Class.rdfs:label: length of perimeter

Class.terms:description: circumference is the length of the outline of a circle or ellipse. it is defined as c = 2*pi*r, where r is the radius.
Class.rdfs:label: circumference

Class.terms:description: A quantity that extends in three dimensions.
Class.rdfs:label: 3D extent quantity

Class.terms:description: volume is the quantity of three-dimensional space enclosed by some closed boundary.
Class.rdfs:label: volume

Class.terms:description: A quantity is an informational entity that gives the magnitude of a property.
Class.rdfs:label: quantity

Class.terms:description: A measurement of a spatial location relative to a frame of reference or other objects.
Class.rdfs:label: position

Class.terms:description: orientation is an angle between the bearer and an axis, or the angle between the bearer and another object.
Class.rdfs:label: orientation

Class.terms:description: A namespace is an informational entity that defines a logical container for a set of symbols or identifiers.
Class.rdfs:label: namespace

Class.terms:description: A data item consists of information that has been collected/generated towards some purpose.
Class.rdfs:label: data item

Class.terms:description: A measurement value is a quantitative description that reflects the magnitude of some attribute.
Class.rdfs:label: measurement value

Class.terms:description: A coordinate is a measurement of position in n-dimensional space.
Class.rdfs:label: coordinate

Class.terms:description: A Cartesian coordinate is the signed distance of a point to some referent line.
Class.rdfs:label: cartesian coordinate

Class.terms:description: A polar coordinate is a position characterized by a distance from a fixed point and an angle from a fixed direction.
Class.rdfs:label: polar coordinate

Class.terms:description: A unit of measurement is a definite magnitude of a physical quantity, defined and adopted by convention and/or by law, that is used as a standard for measurement of the same physical quantity.
Class.rdfs:label: unit of measurement

Class.terms:description: A mathematical entity is an information content entity that are components of a mathematical system or can be defined in mathematical terms.
Class.rdfs:label: mathematical entity

Class.terms:description: A plan is a set of intended actions, through which one expects to achieve a goal.
Class.rdfs:label: plan

Class.terms:description: A generic name is the preferred name provided by manufacturer.
Class.rdfs:label: generic name

Class.terms:description: A language entity implements some language specification for the visual interpretation and is part of some document.
Class.rdfs:label: language entity

Class.terms:description: A visual language entity is a language entity that is manifested within the spectrum of light and can be pereceived and processed by a visual system.
Class.rdfs:label: visual language entity

Class.terms:description: A figure is a graphical entity which consists of a visual (n-dimentional) arrangement of information entities.
Class.rdfs:label: figure

Class.terms:description: An image is an affine projection of a visual entity to a two dimensional surface.
Class.rdfs:label: image

Class.terms:description: A photograph is an image created by light falling on a light-sensitive surface.
Class.rdfs:label: photograph

Class.terms:description: A statistical graph is a figure that displays the relationship among numeric data and/or mathematical functions.
Class.rdfs:label: statistical graph

Class.terms:description: A question is a linguistic expression used to make a request for information.
Class.rdfs:label: question

Class.terms:description: A publication is a document that has been made available by a publisher.
Class.rdfs:label: publication

Class.terms:description: A record is a document containing a collection of statements about some entity.
Class.rdfs:label: record

Class.terms:description: A dataset is a data item that is a collection of data items.
Class.rdfs:label: dataset

Class.terms:description: A specification is a description of the essential technical attributes/requirements for an object or procedure, and may be used to determine that the object / procedure meets its requirements/attributes.
Class.rdfs:label: specification

Class.terms:description: An action specification is a specification composed of a sequence of instructions to achieve some objective.
Class.rdfs:label: action specification

Class.terms:description: An algorithm is an effective method expressed as a finite list of well-defined instructions for calculating a function.
Class.rdfs:label: algorithm

Class.terms:description: A software entity is a computational entity that can be interpreted by or directly executed by a processing unit.
Class.rdfs:label: software entity

Class.terms:description: A software method (also called subroutine, subprogram, procedure, method, function, or routine) is software designed to execute a specific task.
Class.rdfs:label: software method

Class.terms:description: A software module is software composed of a collection of software methods.
Class.rdfs:label: software module

Class.terms:description: A software library is software composed of a collection of software modules and/or software methods in a form that can be statically or dynamically linked to some software application.
Class.rdfs:label: software library

Class.terms:description: A software application is software that can be directly executed by some processing unit.
Class.rdfs:label: software application

Class.terms:description: A software interpreter is a software application that executes some specified input software.
Class.rdfs:label: software interpreter

Class.terms:description: A software script is software whose instructions can be executed using a software interpreter.
Class.rdfs:label: software script

Class.terms:description: Language is a language entity which is the result of encoding and decoding information through systematic creation and usage of systems of symbols, each pairing a specific sign with an intended meaning, established through social conventions
Class.rdfs:label: language

Class.terms:description: A symbol is a proposition about what an entity represents.
Class.rdfs:label: symbol

Class.terms:description: A book is a publication composed of a large number of entries.
Class.rdfs:label: book

Class.terms:description: A chapter is a document section of a book or thesis.
Class.rdfs:label: chapter

Class.terms:description: A character is a language symbol used to construct words.
Class.rdfs:label: character

Class.terms:description: A novel is a fictitious prose narrative of book length, typically representing character and action with some degree of realism.
Class.rdfs:label: novel

Class.terms:description: A paragraph is a self-contained unit of written discourse consisting of one or more sentences.
Class.rdfs:label: paragraph

Class.terms:description: A document section is a component of a document.
Class.rdfs:label: document section

Class.terms:description: A sentence is a grammatical unit consisting of one or more words that bear minimal syntactic relation to the words that precede or follow it.
Class.rdfs:label: sentence

Class.terms:description: A word is the smallest free form (an item that may be expressed in isolation with semantic or pragmatic content) in a language.
Class.rdfs:label: word

Class.terms:description: An identifier is a label that specifically refers to (identifies) an entity (instance/type).
Class.rdfs:label: identifier

Class.terms:description: A name is a label used to identify an entity.
Class.rdfs:label: name

Class.terms:description: A preferred name is the name that is generally used by some organization.
Class.rdfs:label: preferred name

Class.terms:description: A common name is a name that is commonly used.
Class.rdfs:label: common name

Class.terms:description: A brand name is a trademarked and marketed name of a product.
Class.rdfs:label: brand name

Class.terms:description: A scientific name is a name given through scientific nomenclature.
Class.rdfs:label: scientific name

Class.terms:description: A magazine is a periodical that typically contains essays, stories, poems, etc., by many writers, and often photographs and drawings, frequently specializing in a particular subject or area, as hobbies, news, or sports.
Class.rdfs:label: magazine

Class.terms:description: A workflow is an algorithm that is is a depiction of a sequence of operations to achieve one or more objectives.
Class.rdfs:label: workflow

Class.terms:description: An ontology document is a document that contains an ontology.
Class.rdfs:label: ontology document

Class.terms:description: A pattern is a generalized representation of some repeatable concrete or informational item.
Class.rdfs:label: pattern

Class.terms:description: A sequence motif is a pattern of nucleotides in a DNA sequence or amino acids in a protein.
Class.rdfs:label: sequence motif

Class.terms:description: A descriptor (index term, subject term, subject heading) is a term that captures the essence of the topic of a document.
Class.rdfs:label: descriptor

Class.terms:description: A definition is a description that succintly characterizes an entity.
Class.rdfs:label: definition

Class.terms:description: A description is language entity in which elements of a language (formal or natural) are used to characterize an entity.
Class.rdfs:label: description

Class.terms:description: A category is a class of entities having particular shared characteristics.
Class.rdfs:label: category

Class.terms:description: A class is a collection of sets which can be unambiguously defined by a property that all its members share.
Class.rdfs:label: class

Class.terms:description: A web service is a software application that can be accessed over a network, such as the Internet, and executed on a remote system hosting the requested services.
Class.rdfs:label: web service

Class.terms:description: A criterion is a specification to describe properties used for evaluation.
Class.rdfs:label: criterion

Class.terms:description: An inclusion criterion is a criterion that must be present to satisfy some objective.
Class.rdfs:label: inclusion criterion

Class.terms:description: An exclusion criterion is a criterion that must be absent to satistify the objective.
Class.rdfs:label: exclusion criterion

Class.terms:description: A parameter is variable whose value changes the characteristics of a system or a function.
Class.rdfs:label: parameter

Class.terms:description: A keyword is a descriptor in which the association of the word with the entity facilitates information retrieval.
Class.rdfs:label: keyword

Class.terms:description: A document is a bounded physical or digital representation of a body of information designed with the capacity (and usually intent) to communicate.
Class.rdfs:label: document

Class.terms:description: A list is any enumeration of a set of items.
Class.rdfs:label: list

Class.terms:description: A manuscript is a document prior to publication.
Class.rdfs:label: manuscript

Class.terms:description: A note is a brief document.
Class.rdfs:label: note

Class.terms:description: A patent is an information entity granted by a patent issuing authority which confers upon the patenter the sole right to make, use and sell an invention for a set period of time.
Class.rdfs:label: patent

Class.terms:description: An article is a publication that is stand-alone section of a larger work.
Class.rdfs:label: article

Class.terms:description: A blog is a publication accessible at some website and is typically about various experiences.
Class.rdfs:label: blog

Class.terms:description: A book volume is a book that is part of a collection.
Class.rdfs:label: book volume

Class.terms:description: A conference proceedings is a book composed of papers presented at a conference.
Class.rdfs:label: conference proceedings

Class.terms:description: A book series is a collection of books that have been sequentially published.
Class.rdfs:label: book series

Class.terms:description: An edited publication is a publication that has been examined and potentially changed by an editor.
Class.rdfs:label: edited publication

Class.terms:description: A journal is a a peer-reviewed periodical in which scholarship relating to a particular academic discipline is published.
Class.rdfs:label: journal

Class.terms:description: A manual is a document that instructs on the usage of a device.
Class.rdfs:label: manual

Class.terms:description: A periodical is a publication that appears on a regular schedule.
Class.rdfs:label: periodical

Class.terms:description: A newspaper is a periodical publication containing news regarding current events, informative articles, diverse features, editorials, and advertising.
Class.rdfs:label: newspaper

Class.terms:description: A technical report is a publication published by a school or other institution, usually numbered within a series.
Class.rdfs:label: technical report

Class.terms:description: A thesis document is the written research component of a post-secondary institution that contains a statement supported by arguments.
Class.rdfs:label: thesis document

Class.terms:description: An honor's thesis is a thesis prepared as a requirement for an honor's undergraduate degree.
Class.rdfs:label: honor's thesis

Class.terms:description: A Master's thesis is a thesis prepared as a requirement for a Master's degree.
Class.rdfs:label: master's thesis

Class.terms:description: A PhD thesis is a thesis prepared as a requirement for a doctoral degree.
Class.rdfs:label: phd thesis

Class.terms:description: A booklet is a document that lacks a named publisher or sponsoring institution.
Class.rdfs:label: booklet

Class.terms:description: A diary is a document which describes day-to-day experiences.
Class.rdfs:label: diary

Class.terms:description: A bibliographic attribute is an attribute related to publications.
Class.rdfs:label: document component

Class.terms:description: An address is a position that indicates the physical location of some entity using a social convention.
Class.rdfs:label: address

Class.terms:description: An affiliation is a social relation which indicates the partnership between two or more entities.
Class.rdfs:label: affiliation

Class.terms:description: A citation is a textual entity which denotes a source described in the bibliography or reference section of a document.
Class.rdfs:label: citation

Class.terms:description: A document title is a textual entity that summarizes the topic of the document in one sentence.
Class.rdfs:label: document title

Class.terms:description: A reference is a textual entity that describes a single source used in the preparation or development of the work.
Class.rdfs:label: reference

Class.terms:description: A page range denotes the start and end page in some document.
Class.rdfs:label: page range

Class.terms:description: A page total is a textual entity that is about the number of pages in some informational entity.
Class.rdfs:label: page total

Class.terms:description: a label is a term that is associated with some entity
Class.rdfs:label: label

Class.terms:description: A language label is a label that denotes the language of a textual entity.
Class.rdfs:label: language label

Class.terms:description: A first name is a name that denotes a specific individual between members of a group of individuals, whose members usually share the same surname.
Class.rdfs:label: first name

Class.terms:description: A last name (surname) is a name added to a given name and is part of a personal name and is often the family name.
Class.rdfs:label: last name

Class.terms:description: A personal name is a name to identify an individual person and usually comprises of a first name and a last name.
Class.rdfs:label: personal name

Class.terms:description: A legal name is a name given at birth, or which appears on their birth certificate, marriage certificate, or change of name certificate.
Class.rdfs:label: legal name

Class.terms:description: A title is a textual entity that summarily describes some entity.
Class.rdfs:label: title

Class.terms:description: A document version is a version of a work in some sequence of derivative works.
Class.rdfs:label: document version

Class.terms:description: An abstract section is a document section that provides brief summary of a document that explains the main argument(s), topic(s) or findings.
Class.rdfs:label: abstract section

Class.terms:description: An acknowledgements section is a document section that identifies individuals, groups or organizations for their support in the development of the work.
Class.rdfs:label: acknowledgements section

Class.terms:description: An author contribution section is a document section that describes the contribution of the authors.
Class.rdfs:label: author contribution section

Class.terms:description: An author section is a document section that lists the contributing authors.
Class.rdfs:label: author section

Class.terms:description: A bibliography section is a document section that is composed of a list of references used in the development of the work.
Class.rdfs:label: bibliography section

Class.terms:description: A copyright section is a document section that contains a notice of copyright.
Class.rdfs:label: copyright section

Class.terms:description: A correspondence section is a document section that contains the details for contacting the corresponding author.
Class.rdfs:label: correspondence section

Class.terms:description: The discussion section is a document section containing a summary of the findings, a reflection on the significance of findings, comparison with related work, among others.
Class.rdfs:label: discussion section

Class.terms:description: An introduction section is a document section that generally provides background, motivation and goals of the work.
Class.rdfs:label: introduction section

Class.terms:description: The materials and methods section is a document section containing a description of the materials and methods used in the study.
Class.rdfs:label: materials and methods section

Class.terms:description: The materials section is a document section containing a description of the materials used in the study.
Class.rdfs:label: materials section

Class.terms:description: The methods section is a document section containing a description of the methods used in the study.
Class.rdfs:label: methods section

Class.terms:description: The results section is a document section describing the main findings of the study.
Class.rdfs:label: results section

Class.terms:description: The table of contents is a document section that lists all sections (and optionally subsections) in a sequential order along with their page number.
Class.rdfs:label: table of contents

Class.terms:description: Implication is a logical operator that holds between a set T of propositions and a proposition B, when every model (or interpretation or valuation) of T is also a model of B.
Class.rdfs:label: implies (->)

Class.terms:description: A namespace label is a short name for a namespace.
Class.rdfs:label: namespace label

Class.terms:description: A logical operator is a unary or binary relation to construct logical expressions.
Class.rdfs:label: logical operator

Class.terms:description: AND is a logical operator that has the value true if both of its operands are true, otherwise a value of false.
Class.rdfs:label: conjunction (and)

Class.terms:description: A proposition is a sentence expressing something true or false.
Class.rdfs:label: proposition

Class.terms:description: A dimensionless quantity is a quantity that has no associated unit.
Class.rdfs:label: dimensionless quantity

Class.terms:description: A dimensional quantity is a quantity that has an associated unit.
Class.rdfs:label: dimensional quantity

Class.terms:description: An argument is a set of one or more declarative sentences (or propositions) known as the premises along with another declarative sentence (or proposition) known as the conclusion.
Class.rdfs:label: argument

Class.terms:description: A premise is a proposition of an argument from which the conclusion is drawn.
Class.rdfs:label: premise

Class.terms:description: A conclusion is a proposition which is reached after considering the evidence, arguments or premises.
Class.rdfs:label: conclusion

Class.terms:description: A deductive argument is an argument that asserts that the truth of the conclusion is a logical consequence of the premises.
Class.rdfs:label: deductive argument

Class.terms:description: An inductive argument is an argument that asserts that the truth of the conclusion is supported by the premises.
Class.rdfs:label: inductive argument

Class.terms:description: A sound argument is a valid argument with true premises.
Class.rdfs:label: sound argument

Class.terms:description: A valid argument is an argument where the truth of the conclusion is a logical consequence of the premises and (consequently) its corresponding conditional is a necessary truth.
Class.rdfs:label: valid argument

Class.terms:description: An invalid argument is an argument where the truth of the conclusion is false because it is not a logical consequence of the premises.
Class.rdfs:label: invalid argument

Class.terms:description: A term is a word or phrase used to denote one or more entities.
Class.rdfs:label: term

Class.terms:description: mass is the quality of the amount of substance.
Class.rdfs:label: mass

Class.terms:description: OR is a logical operator that results in true whenever one or more of its operands are true.
Class.rdfs:label: disjunction (or)

Class.terms:description: NOT is a logical operator in that has the value true if its operand is false.
Class.rdfs:label: negation (not)

Class.terms:description: XOR, also called exclusive disjunction or (symbolized XOR, EOR, EXOR, or ), is a type of logical disjunction on two operands that results in a value of true if exactly one of the operands has a value of true.
Class.rdfs:label: exclusive disjunction (xor)

Class.terms:description: A hypothesis is a proposed explanation for a phenomenon.
Class.rdfs:label: hypothesis

Class.terms:description: An academic organization is a lawfully recognized organization that confers diplomas, degrees and other forms of recognition of academic achievement.
Class.rdfs:label: academic organization

Class.terms:description: A social relation is a social entity that describes a relationship between two or more individuals or groups.
Class.rdfs:label: social relation

Class.terms:description: A set is a collection of entities, for which there may be zero members.
Class.rdfs:label: set

Class.terms:description: A university is an institution of higher education and research which grants academic degrees in a variety of subjects and provides both undergraduate education and postgraduate education.
Class.rdfs:label: university

Class.terms:description: A collection of documents is a non-zero set of documents.
Class.rdfs:label: collection of documents

Class.terms:description: A website is a collection of documents published on the World Wide Web.
Class.rdfs:label: website

Class.terms:description: A movie is a series of images that are displayed in rapid succession to give the impression of movement.
Class.rdfs:label: movie

Class.terms:description: An excerpt is a contiguous or discontiguous portion of a document.
Class.rdfs:label: excerpt

Class.terms:description: A quote is a excerpt that is attributed to a particular source.
Class.rdfs:label: quote

Class.terms:description: A geographic image is a photograph of some geographical area.
Class.rdfs:label: geographic image

Class.terms:description: A web page is a document that is published according to World Wide Web standards.
Class.rdfs:label: web page

Class.terms:description: Email message is a digital document that is composed of a header and a body and is transmitted using the SMTP protocol.
Class.rdfs:label: email

Class.terms:description: process number is a number associated with a process that denotes its ordinal position in a set of processes.
Class.rdfs:label: process number

Class.terms:description: A letter is a document that contains a personal communication from one part to another.
Class.rdfs:label: letter

Class.terms:description: An edition number is count of a literary work edited and published, as by a certain editor or in a certain manner including being printed during some interval of time.
Class.rdfs:label: edition number

Class.terms:description: volume number is a count of a sequence of periodicals.
Class.rdfs:label: volume number

Class.terms:description: A functional specification is a specification that describes the characteristics of an object.
Class.rdfs:label: functional specification

Class.terms:description: A design specification is a specification that provides precise and explicit information about the requirements for a product design.
Class.rdfs:label: design specification

Class.terms:description: A specification for spatial location is an effective specification towards representation spatial position or spatial data.
Class.rdfs:label: spatial specification

Class.terms:description: Longitude is a geographic position that refers to the angle east or west of a reference meridian between the two geographical poles to another meridian that passes through an arbitrary point.
Class.rdfs:label: longitude

Class.terms:description: Latitude is a geographic coordinate which refers to the angle from a point on the Earth's surface to the equatorial plane
Class.rdfs:label: latitude

Class.terms:description: A coordinate system is a specification for spatial location that uses a set of numbers, or coordinates, to uniquely determine the position of a point or other geometric element.
Class.rdfs:label: coordinate system

Class.terms:description: A Cartesian coordinate system specifies each point uniquely in a plane by a pair of numerical coordinates, which are the signed distances from the point to two fixed perpendicular directed lines, measured in the same unit of length.
Class.rdfs:label: cartesian coordinate system

Class.terms:description: A concept is term that refers to a generalization of a set of attributes or entities.
Class.rdfs:label: concept

Class.terms:description: A polar coordinate system is a two-dimensional coordinate system in which each point on a plane is determined by a distance from a fixed point and an angle from a fixed direction.
Class.rdfs:label: polar coordinate system

Class.terms:description: A positional description is a description of location using some system or frame of reference.
Class.rdfs:label: positional identifier

Class.terms:description: A cylindrical coordinate system is a three-dimensional coordinate system that specifies point positions by the distance from a chosen reference axis, the direction from the axis relative to a chosen reference direction, and the distance from a chosen reference plane perpendicular to the axis.
Class.rdfs:label: cylindrical coordinate system

Class.terms:description: A spherical coordinate system is a coordinate system for three-dimensional space where the position of a point is specified by three numbers: the radial distance of that point from a fixed origin, its polar angle measured from a fixed zenith direction, and the azimuth angle of its orthogonal projection on a reference plane that passes through the origin and is orthogonal to the zenith, measured from a fixed reference direction on that plane.
Class.rdfs:label: spherical coordinate system

Class.terms:description: An OWL ontology is an ontology as specified by the W3C OWL specification.
Class.rdfs:label: OWL ontology

Class.terms:description: A 3D cartesian coordinate is a coordinate that is composed of an x, y and z coordinate.
Class.rdfs:label: 3D cartesian coordinate

Class.terms:description: An objective is a proposition that indicates a planned or anticipated outcome.
Class.rdfs:label: objective

Class.terms:description: purpose is the reason for which something is done or created or for which something exists.
Class.rdfs:label: purpose

Class.terms:description: A belief is a proposition that is believed to be true.
Class.rdfs:label: belief

Class.terms:description: A number is a mathematical object used to count, label, and measure.
Class.rdfs:label: number

Class.terms:description: A variable is a value that may change within the scope of a given problem or set of operations.
Class.rdfs:label: variable

Class.terms:description: An equation is a mathematical statement that asserts the equality of two expressions.
Class.rdfs:label: equation

Class.terms:description: time measurement is a measurement value of the duration of some interval of time or a particular instant of time (against some frame of reference).
Class.schema:comment: Time intervals are specified as date/datetime ranges.
Class.resource:example: the duration of my life; the duration of a surgical procedure, the moment of death
Class.rdfs:label: time measurement

Class.terms:description: A file is an information-bearing object that contains a physical embodiment of some information using a particular character encoding.
Class.rdfs:label: file

Class.terms:description: An x cartesian coordinate is the coordinate of an object onto the x-axis of a cartesian coordinate system.
Class.rdfs:label: x cartesian coordinate

Class.terms:description: An y cartesian coordinate is the coordinate of an object onto the y-axis of a cartesian coordinate system.
Class.rdfs:label: y cartesian coordinate

Class.terms:description: A z cartesian coordinate is the coordinate of an object onto the z-axis of a cartesian coordinate system.
Class.rdfs:label: z cartesian coordinate

Class.terms:description: A study group is a group of individuals that are subjects in an observational or intervention study.
Class.rdfs:label: study group

Class.terms:description: A time internval is a contiguous temporal region having some duration.
Class.rdfs:label: time interval

Class.terms:description: A time instant is a temporal region which occurs instantaneously, e.g. having no duration.
Class.resource:example: at this moment; the moment at which a finger is detached in an industrial accident; the moment at which a child is born; the moment of death
Class.rdfs:label: time instant

Class.terms:description: A table is a figure that consists of an ordered arrangement of columns and rows.
Class.rdfs:label: table

Class.terms:description: A scatterplot is a statistical graph which uses Cartesian coordinates to display values for two variables for a set of data. The data is displayed as a collection of points, each having the value of one variable determining the position on the horizontal axis and the value of the other variable determining the position on the vertical axis.
Class.rdfs:label: scatterplot

Class.terms:description: A year is a period of time taken by a planet to make one revolution around the sun.
Class.rdfs:label: year

Class.terms:description: A month is a period of time that divides the year.
Class.rdfs:label: month

Class.terms:description: A day is a period of 24 hours.
Class.rdfs:label: day

Class.terms:description: A century is a period of one hundred years.
Class.rdfs:label: century

Class.terms:description: A millenium is a period of 1000 years
Class.rdfs:label: millenium

Class.terms:description: An hour is a period of 60 minutes.
Class.rdfs:label: hour

Class.terms:description: A minute is a period of 60 seconds.
Class.rdfs:label: minute

Class.terms:description: A second (symbol: s) is the base unit of time in the International System of Units (SI) and is the second division of the hour by sixty, the first division by 60 being the minute.
Class.rdfs:label: second

Class.terms:description: A 2D cartesian point is a point whose position is specified along two dimensions using Cartesian coordinates.
Class.rdfs:label: 2D cartesian point

Class.terms:description: Altitude is a distance above sea level.
Class.rdfs:label: altitude

Class.terms:description: The center of mass (aka barycenter) is the weighted average location of all the mass in a body or group of bodies.
Class.rdfs:label: center of mass

Class.terms:description: A 3D cartesian point is a point whose position is specified along three dimensions using Cartesian coordinates.
Class.rdfs:label: 3D cartesian point

Class.terms:description: A 1D cartesian point is a point whose position is specified along a single dimension using Cartesian coordinates.
Class.rdfs:label: 1D cartesian point

Class.terms:description: A line graph is a statistical graph in which lines contains the evaluation of functions or individual points connected by line segments.
Class.resource:example: Graph 1 in http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: line graph

Class.terms:description: A bar graph is a statistical graph with rectangular bars of lengths proportional to that value that they represent.
Class.resource:example: Graphs 3,4,5 in http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: bar graph

Class.terms:description: A horizontal bar graph is a bar graph in which the rectangular bars are horizontally oriented in space.
Class.resource:example: Graph 3 in http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: horizontal bar graph

Class.terms:description: A vertical bar graph is a bar graph in which the rectangular bars are vertically oriented in space.
Class.resource:example: Graph 4,5 in http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: vertical bar graph

Class.terms:description: A stacked bar graph is a bar graph in which each rectangular bar is partioned by the categorical value of each series of data.
Class.resource:example: Graphs 6,7 in http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: stacked bar graph

Class.terms:description: A line-bar graph statistical graph that contains both lines and bars.
Class.resource:example: Graph 8 in http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: line-bar graph

Class.terms:description: A figure part is a part of a figure.
Class.rdfs:label: figure part

Class.terms:description: A plot is a part of a figure that corresponds to the spatial region between the set of axes.
Class.resource:example: The square portion of the chart bounded by lines that overlap with the two axes in Graph 1 of http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: plot

Class.terms:description: An axis is a line segment that is part of a statistical graph in which the position along the line corresponds to a numeric or categorical value.
Class.schema:comment: The value of a plotted geometric objects (e.g. point) can be obtained from the perpendicular projection of the position of the object onto the axis. Axis may also be associated with a textual description of what the values on the axis represents.
Class.resource:example: The left vertical and bottom horizontal lines with tickmarks in Graph 1 http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: axis

Class.terms:description: A Cartesian coordinate axis is an axis whose behavior follows that of a Cartesian coordinate system.
Class.rdfs:label: Cartesian coordinate axis

Class.terms:description: An x-axis is a Cartesian coordinate axis that is aligned with the horizon.
Class.schema:comment: In most figures, this axis represents categories, such as months, market segments, or other non-numeric data.
Class.resource:example: The horizontal axis in http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: x-axis

Class.terms:description: A y-axis is a Cartesian coordinate axis that is spatially oriented perpendicular to the x-axis.
Class.rdfs:label: y-axis

Class.terms:description: A z-axis is a Cartesian coordinate axis that is spatially oriented normal to the plane formed by the x- and y-axes.
Class.rdfs:label: z-axis

Class.terms:description: A category axis is an axis in which the position along the line is partioned into categories.
Class.resource:example: The horizontal axis corresponding to months of the year in graph 4 of http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: category axis

Class.terms:description: A primary category axis is a category axis that either defines the sole value range or holds the larger set of categorical values specified by the secondary category axis.
Class.resource:example: The category axis that corresponds to years in Graph 1 of http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: primary category axis

Class.terms:description: A secondary category axis is a category axis that defines a finer granular part (or subset) of the value range of the primary category axis.
Class.resource:example: The category axis that corresponds to months in Graph 1 of http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: secondary category axis

Class.terms:description: A value axis is an axis in which the position along the line is partioned into numeric values.
Class.schema:comment: A value axis holds the properties of having a minimum and a maximum value, and is usually associated with tickmarks that indicate intervals along the axis.
Class.resource:example: The value axis that ranges from 3.0 to 7.4 and corresponds to billions of dollars in Graph 1 of http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: value axis

Class.terms:description: A left value axis is a value axis that is spatially positioned to the left of the plot area.
Class.resource:example: The value axis that ranges from 3.0 to 7.4 and corresponds to billions of dollars in Graph 1 of http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: left value axis

Class.terms:description: A right value axis is a value axis that is spatially positioned to the right of the plot area.
Class.rdfs:label: right value axis

Class.terms:description: A scaled value axis is a value axis in which the value range was subject to a mathematic transformation.
Class.rdfs:label: scaled value axis

Class.terms:description: A linear value axis is a value axis that corresponds to a scaling factor of 1 of the value range.
Class.rdfs:label: linear value axis

Class.terms:description: A logarithmic value axis is a scaled value axis that corresponds to a scaling factor of the logarithm of the value range.
Class.rdfs:label: logarithmic value axis

Class.terms:description: A data series is a data set composed of related values displayed in a statistical graph.
Class.resource:example: Example: The two series that correspond to "Seasonally adjusted" and "Trend" are composed of the seasonally adjusted value of permits in each month and values from a trend derived from some mathematical tranformation across those values, respectively, in Graph 1 of http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: data series

Class.terms:description: A data point is a point that which corresponds to the projection of the values of measurement data against the axes of a statistical graph.
Class.rdfs:label: data point

Class.terms:description: A global maximum stationary point is a data point that corresponds to a measurement value is larger than that of all other plotted datapoints.
Class.rdfs:label: global maximal stationary point

Class.terms:description: A global minimum data point is a data point that corresponds to a measurement value is smaller than that of all other plotted datapoints.
Class.rdfs:label: global minimal stationary point

Class.terms:description: A legend is a part of a figure that associates textual descriptions with symbols pertaining to plotted entities.
Class.resource:example: The colored line segments and the adjacent textual descriptions in Graph 1 of http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: legend

Class.terms:description: A primary title is a title that should be first used in describing some entity.
Class.rdfs:label: primary title

Class.terms:description: A secondary title is a title of lesser importance that should be used after the first title in describing some entity.
Class.rdfs:label: secondary title

Class.terms:description: scientific data is data obtained from some scientific procedure.
Class.rdfs:label: scientific data

Class.terms:description: A primary graph title is a primary title that describes a statistical graph.
Class.resource:example: "Total value of permits increased slightly in December" in Graph 1 of http://tinyurl.com/opwnvm
Class.rdfs:label: primary graph title

Class.terms:description: A secondary graph title is a secondary title that describes a statistical graph.
Class.rdfs:label: secondary graph title

Class.terms:description: A phrase is a group of words functioning as a single unit in the syntax of a sentence.
Class.rdfs:label: phrase

Class.terms:description: A clause consists of a subject and a predicate.
Class.rdfs:label: clause

Class.terms:description: A polygon vertex is a terminal point at which two polygon edges meet and are part of a polygon.
Class.rdfs:label: polygon vertex

Class.terms:description: A polygon edge is a line segment joining two polygon vertices.
Class.rdfs:label: polygon edge

Class.terms:description: A polyhedral skeleton is a collection of polygon edges.
Class.rdfs:label: polyhedral skeleton

Class.terms:description: A polygonal face is a polygon bounded by a circuit of polygon edges, and includes the flat (plane) region inside the boundary.
Class.rdfs:label: polygonal face

Class.terms:description: A polyhedral surface is composed of polygonal faces.
Class.rdfs:label: polyhedral surface

Class.terms:description: A polygon is a planar entity that is bounded by a closed path or circuit, composed of a finite connected sequence3 of straight line segments.
Class.rdfs:label: polygon

Class.terms:description: A geometric entity is an information content entity that pertains to the structure and topology of a space.
Class.rdfs:label: geometric entity

Class.terms:description: A point is a geometric entity that is located in a zero-dimensional spatial region and whose position is defined by its coordinates in some coordinate system.
Class.rdfs:label: point

Class.terms:description: An endpoint is a terminal point that is the last of an ordered pair of points.
Class.rdfs:label: endpoint

Class.terms:description: A start point is a terminal point which is the first of an ordered pair of points.
Class.rdfs:label: start point

Class.terms:description: A model is a representation of some thing.
Class.rdfs:label: model

Class.terms:description: A line is curve that extends in a single dimension (e.g. straight line; exhibits no curvature), and is composed of at least two fully connected points.
Class.rdfs:label: line

Class.terms:description: A line segment is a line and a part of a curve that is (inclusively) bounded by two terminal points.
Class.rdfs:label: line segment

Class.terms:description: A tick mark is a line segment that is spatially positioned perpendicular to the axis of a statistical graph and indicates the position of a specific numeric value (which may be indicated by an adjacent value label) on a value axis, or is one of a pair of tick marks that delineates the boundary of a categorical value (which may be indicated by an adjacent category label) on the categorical axis.
Class.rdfs:label: tick mark

Class.terms:description: A major tick mark is a tick mark that indicates the position of a specific numeric value and is adjacent to its value label on the value axis, or is one of a pair of tick marks that delineates the boundary of a categorical value indicated by an adjacent category label on the categorical axis.
Class.rdfs:label: major tick mark

Class.terms:description: A minor tick mark is a tick mark that indicates the position of a specific numeric value but has no adjacent value label, or is one of a pair of tick marks that delineates the boundary of a categorical value but has no adjacent category label on the categorical axis.
Class.rdfs:label: minor tick mark

Class.terms:description: A ray is a line which that is bounded by a startpoint and extends outwards infinitely along one dimension.
Class.rdfs:label: ray

Class.terms:description: A quadrilateral is a polygon with composed of four points and four line segments, in which each point is fully connected to two other points.
Class.rdfs:label: quadrilateral

Class.terms:description: A rectangle is a quadrilateral in which one pair of line segments are parallel and the other pair are perpendicular to the first pair.
Class.rdfs:label: rectangle

Class.terms:description: A bar is a rectangle that is located in the plot of a statistical graph in which its length is proportional to the values that it represents.
Class.rdfs:label: bar

Class.terms:description: A triangle is a polygon composed of three points and three line segments, in which each point is fully connected to another point along through the line segment.
Class.rdfs:label: triangle

Class.terms:description: A directed line segment is a line segment that is contained by an ordered pair of endpoints (a start point and an endpoint).
Class.rdfs:label: directed line segment

Class.terms:description: An arrowed line is a directed line segment in which one or both endpoints is tangentially part of a triangle that bisects the line.
Class.rdfs:label: arrowed line segment

Class.terms:description: A single arrowed line is directed line in which the endpoint is tangentially part of a triangle that bisects the line.
Class.rdfs:label: single arrowed line segment

Class.terms:description: A double arrowed line is an arrowed line in which both terminal points are tangentially part of different triangles that bisect the line.
Class.rdfs:label: double arrowed line segment

Class.terms:description: A horizontal line is a line that is positionally oriented with the horizon.
Class.rdfs:label: horizontal line

Class.terms:description: A vertical line is a line that is positionally oriented perpendicular to the horizon.
Class.rdfs:label: vertical line

Class.terms:description: A trend line is a line, line segment or ray that is part of a statistical graph which indicates a statistical or visual direction across categorical or value data.
Class.rdfs:label: trend line

Class.terms:description: An increasing line is a line segment in which the startpoint and endpoint are ordered along one dimension and the difference of values in a second dimension is positive.
Class.rdfs:label: increasing line

Class.terms:description: An decreasing line is a line segment in which the startpoint and endpoint are ordered along one dimension and the difference of values in a second dimension is negative.
Class.rdfs:label: decreasing line

Class.terms:description: An plateau line is a line segment in which the startpoint and endpoint are ordered along one dimension and the difference of values in a second dimension is zero.
Class.rdfs:label: plateau line

Class.terms:description: A drop line is a statistical graph line that vertically or horizontally connects a data series line with a value axis in a statistical graph.
Class.rdfs:label: drop line

Class.terms:description: A terminal point is a point that defines the finite extension of a line.
Class.rdfs:label: terminal point

Class.terms:description: A surface normal is a vector that is perpendicular to a flat surface.
Class.rdfs:label: surface normal

Class.terms:description: A positionally oriented line is a line that is positioned against some axis of reference.
Class.rdfs:label: positionally oriented line

Class.terms:description: A statistical graph line is a line used in a statistical graph to communicate some trend or feature of the embedded data.
Class.rdfs:label: statistical graph line

Class.terms:description: An infinite line is a line that extends outwards in both directions of a single dimensional and is not bounded by terminal points.
Class.rdfs:label: infinite line

Class.terms:description: A vector is a line which that is bounded by a startpoint and extends outwards along one dimension.
Class.rdfs:label: vector

Class.terms:description: A vertext normal is the normalized average of the surface normals of the faces that contain that vertex.
Class.rdfs:label: vertex normal

Class.terms:description: A polyline is a connected sequence of line segments.
Class.resource:hasSynonym: polygonal chain, polygonal curve, polygonal path, piecewise linear curve
Class.rdfs:label: polyline

Class.terms:description: A collection of points is a geometric entity that contains a non-zero set of geometric points.
Class.rdfs:label: collection of points

Class.terms:description: A diffusion equation describes density fluctuations in a material undergoing diffusion.
Class.rdfs:label: diffusion equation

Class.terms:description: A movement equation describes the displacement of an object in space over time.
Class.rdfs:label: movement equation

Class.terms:description: An ordinary differential equation (ODE) is a differential equation in which the unknown function (also known as the dependent variable) is a function of a single independent variable.
Class.rdfs:label: ordinary differential equation

Class.terms:description: A partial differential equation (PDE) is a differential equation in which the unknown function is a function of multiple independent variables and the equation involves its partial derivatives.
Class.rdfs:label: partial differential equation

Class.terms:description: A differential equation is a mathematical equation for an unknown function of one or several variables that relates the values of the function itself and its derivatives of various orders.
Class.rdfs:label: differential equation

Class.terms:description: An idea is a proposition about some object of conceptual thought.
Class.rdfs:label: idea

Class.terms:description: structure is the specification that refers to the composition and arrangement of parts of an object.
Class.rdfs:label: structure

Class.terms:description: A computational entity is an information content entity operated on using some computational system.
Class.rdfs:label: computational entity

Class.terms:description: A curve is a geometric entity that may be located in n-dimensional spatial region whose extension may be n-dimensional, is composed of at least two fully connected points and does not intersect itself.
Class.rdfs:label: curve

Class.terms:description: A representation is a entity that in some way represents another entity (or attribute thereof).
Class.rdfs:label: representation

Class.terms:description: A ordinal position is a number that designates the position of an entity from the first entity in an ordered sequence of entities.
Class.rdfs:label: ordinal position

Class.terms:description: A collection is a set for which there exists at least one member, although any member need not to exist at any point in the collection's existence.
Class.rdfs:label: collection

Class.terms:description: An empty set is a set for which there are exactly 0 members.
Class.rdfs:label: empty set

Class.terms:description: A standard is a socially-agreed upon specification.
Class.rdfs:label: standard

Class.terms:description: A regulatory authority is an organization responsible for exercising regulatory or supervisory capacity in some area of human activity.
Class.rdfs:label: regulatory authority

Class.terms:description: A collective is a group of entities that share or are motivated by at least one common issue or interest, or work together on a specific project(s) to achieve a common objective.
Class.rdfs:label: collective

Class.terms:description: A formal specification is a mathematical description of software or hardware that may be used to develop an implementation.
Class.rdfs:label: formal specification

Class.terms:description: An RDFS ontology is an ontology that conforms to the syntax and semantics of the Resource Description Framework Schema (RDFS).
Class.rdfs:label: RDFS ontology

Class.terms:description: An OBO ontology is an ontology document as specified by the Open Biological Ontology community.
Class.rdfs:label: OBO ontology

Class.terms:description: chemical structure is the structure of a chemical entity in terms of its molecular geometry and electronic structure.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical structure

Class.terms:description: molecular structure is the spatial arrangement of atoms in a molecule and the chemical bonds that hold the atoms together.
Class.rdfs:label: molecular structure

Class.terms:description: A probability measure is quantity of how likely it is that some event will occur.
Class.rdfs:label: probability measure

Class.terms:description: A process model is a representation of some process.
Class.rdfs:label: process model

Class.terms:description: An object model is a representation of an object.
Class.rdfs:label: object model

Class.terms:description: A textual entity is language entity that is manifested as a sequence of one or more distinct characters.
Class.rdfs:label: textual entity

Class.terms:description: A version label is a label for a particular form or variation of an earlier or original type.
Class.rdfs:label: version label

Class.terms:description: A software version label is a version label for a piece of software.
Class.resource:example: major.minor[.build[.revision]]
Class.rdfs:label: software version label

Class.terms:description: A start time is a time instant pertaining to the time at which a process begins.
Class.rdfs:label: start time

Class.terms:description: An end time is a time instant pertaining to the time at which a process ends.
Class.rdfs:label: end time

Class.terms:description: A unique identifier is an identifier that uniquely identifies some thing.
Class.rdfs:label: unique identifier

Class.terms:description: A justification is a proposition that defends, explains or excuses some argument.
Class.rdfs:label: justification

Class.terms:description: An academic department is a division of a university or school faculty devoted to a particular academic discipline.
Class.rdfs:label: academic department

Class.terms:description: institute is a society or organization having a object or common factor, and is normally applied to those with a scientific, educational, or social objective.
Class.rdfs:label: institute

Class.terms:description: A corporation is an organization that is granted a charter recognizing it as a separate legal entity.
Class.rdfs:label: corporation

Class.terms:description: A specification of an object, manifested by an agent, intended to accomplish goals, in a particular environment, using a set of primitive components, satisfying a set of requirements, subject to constraints.
Class.rdfs:label: design

Class.terms:description: A chemical identifier is an identifier for a chemical entity
Class.rdfs:label: chemical identifier

Class.terms:description: A record identifier is an identifier for a database entry.
Class.rdfs:label: record identifier

Class.terms:description: A physical entity identifier is an identifier for a physical entity.
Class.rdfs:label: physical entity identifier

Class.terms:description: An informational entity identifier is an identifier for an informational entity.
Class.rdfs:label: informational entity identifier

Class.terms:description: A molecular identifier is an identifier for a molecular entity.
Class.rdfs:label: molecular identifier

Class.terms:description: A curve segment is a part of a curve that consists of at least three points.
Class.rdfs:label: curve segment

Class.terms:description: A stationary point is a point that is part of a curve in which the derivative at that point is zero, and hence its value is at least a local maximum or minimum.
Class.rdfs:label: stationary point

Class.terms:description: A local maximum stationary point is a point that has a higher value in some axis than adjacent points.
Class.rdfs:label: local maximum stationary point

Class.terms:description: A local minimum stationary point is a point that has a lower value in some axis than adjacent points.
Class.rdfs:label: local minimum stationary point

Class.terms:description: A database is a set of tables.
Class.rdfs:label: database

Class.terms:description: A row represents a single, implicitly structured data item in a table.
Class.rdfs:label: row

Class.terms:description: A column is a vertical sequence of cells in a cellular automata.
Class.rdfs:label: column

Class.terms:description: A database table is a set of named columns with zero or more rows composed of cells that contain column values and is part of a database.
Class.rdfs:label: database table

Class.terms:description: The minimal unit of a cellular automaton that can change state and has an associated behavior.
Class.rdfs:label: cell (informational)

Class.terms:description: A database entry is a single, implicitly structured data item in a table.
Class.rdfs:label: database entry

Class.terms:description: A database collumn is a column in a database table.
Class.rdfs:label: database column

Class.terms:description: A unique cell is a cell that contains a unique value in the cellular automaton.
Class.rdfs:label: unique cell

Class.terms:description: A referenceing cell is a cell of a cellular automata that refers to another cell.
Class.rdfs:label: referencing cell

Class.terms:description: A referent cell is a cell that is the referent of some function or pointer.
Class.rdfs:label: referent cell

Class.terms:description: A database key is an informational entity whose value is constructed from one or more database columns.
Class.rdfs:label: database key

Class.terms:description: A primary database key is a database key that identifies every row of a table.
Class.rdfs:label: primary database key

Class.terms:description: A foreign database key is a database key that refers to a key in some table.
Class.rdfs:label: foreign database key

Class.terms:description: A p-value or probability value is the probability of obtaining a test statistic at least as extreme as the one that was actually observed, assuming that the null hypothesis is true
Class.rdfs:label: probability value

Class.terms:description: A street name is the token given to identify a particular street.
Class.rdfs:label: street name

Class.terms:description: A postal code is a geographic coordinate composed of a series of letters and/or digits appended to a postal address for the purpose of sorting mail.
Class.rdfs:label: postal code

Class.terms:description: An apartment number is the number assigned to identify an apartment in a building of apartments.
Class.rdfs:label: apartment number

Class.terms:description: The uncertainty value (margin of error) of a measurement is a range of values likely to enclose the true value.
Class.rdfs:label: uncertainty value

Class.terms:description: A standard deviation (represented by the symbol ) is the quantity of variation from the average (mean, or expected value).
Class.rdfs:label: standard deviation

Class.terms:description: A versioned record is a record for which there exists another variant based that was derived via modification of the facts.
Class.rdfs:label: versioned record

Class.terms:description: An answer is a reply to a question.
Class.rdfs:label: answer

Class.terms:description: A verbal language entity is a language entity that is manifested through sound.
Class.rdfs:label: verbal language entity

Class.terms:description: A page number is the count of a page in a sequence of pages.
Class.rdfs:label: page number

Class.terms:description: A linear position is the position of some object against a linear positioning system.
Class.rdfs:label: linear position

Class.terms:description: A sequence element position is the position of an element of a linear sequence.
Class.rdfs:label: sequence element position

Class.terms:description: A sequence start position is the start position for a sequence of characters.
Class.rdfs:label: sequence start position

Class.terms:description: A sequence end position is the position of the last character in a sequence of characters relative to some linear frame of reference.
Class.rdfs:label: sequence end position

Class.terms:description: The number of elements of a finite set of objects.
Class.rdfs:label: count

Class.terms:description: A Uniform Resource Locator or Universal Resource Locator (URL) is a specific character string that constitutes a reference to an Internet resource.
Class.rdfs:label: URL

Class.terms:description: An assocation is a relationship between two or more entities derived by some informational analysis.
Class.rdfs:label: association

Class.terms:description: A statistical association is any relationship between two measured quantities that renders them statistically dependent.
Class.rdfs:label: statistical association

Class.terms:description: A top value axis is a value axis that is spatially positioned to the top of the plot area.
Class.rdfs:label: top value axis

Class.terms:description: A bottom value axis is a value axis that is spatially positioned to the bottom of the plot area.
Class.rdfs:label: bottom value axis

Class.terms:description: A chart is a figure that displays the relationship among tabular numeric data, functions or some kinds of qualitative structures.
Class.rdfs:label: chart

Class.terms:description: A map is a a visual representation of an area that depicts the relationship between elements of that space.
Class.rdfs:label: map

Class.terms:description: A heatmap is a graphical representation of data where the individual values contained in a matrix are represented as colors.
Class.rdfs:label: heatmap

Class.terms:description: A streamgraph is a multi-line stacked graph that yields the appearance of continuous y-values across the x-axis.
Class.rdfs:label: streamgraph

Class.terms:description: A boxplot (box-and-whisker diagram) is a convenient way of graphically depicting groups of numerical data through their five-number summaries: the smallest observation (sample minimum), lower quartile (Q1), median (Q2), upper quartile (Q3), and largest observation (sample maximum).
Class.rdfs:label: boxplot

Class.terms:description: A geographic heatmap is a graphical representation of data over a geographic region where individual values are represented as colors.
Class.rdfs:label: geographic heatmap

Class.terms:description: A histogram is a graphical representation of data which consists of tabular frequencies, shown as adjacent rectangles, over discrete intervals (bins) , with an area equal to the frequency of the observations in the interval.
Class.rdfs:label: histogram

Class.terms:description: A measurement scale is a functional specification that specifies an allowed range of categories or values.
Class.rdfs:label: measurement scale

Class.terms:description: A nominal scale of measurement only specifies a limited set of categories.
Class.rdfs:label: nomimal scale

Class.terms:description: A binary scale is a measurement scale that specifies a choice between two values.
Class.rdfs:label: binary scale

Class.terms:description: A numeric scale of measurement is one that only specifies numeric values.
Class.rdfs:label: numeric scale

Class.terms:description: A decimal scale of measurement is one that only specifies decimal values.
Class.rdfs:label: decimal scale

Class.terms:description: An integer scale of measurement is one that only specifies integer values.
Class.rdfs:label: integer scale

Class.terms:description: An independent variable is a variable that may take on different values independent of other elements in a system.
Class.rdfs:label: independent variable

Class.terms:description: A dependent variable is one whose value changes as a consequence of changes in other values in the system.
Class.rdfs:label: dependent variable

Class.terms:description: A Gantt chart is a bar chart that illustrates a project schedule.
Class.rdfs:label: Gantt chart

Class.terms:description: A correlation is a statistical relationship involving dependence between two random variables or datasets.
Class.rdfs:label: correlation

Class.terms:description: A television program is a audiovisual media that is produced and broadcast using a television.
Class.rdfs:label: television program

Class.terms:description: A pie chart is a circular chart divided into sectors each of whose length is proportional to the quantity it represents.
Class.rdfs:label: pie chart

Class.terms:description: A matrix chart summarizes a multidimensional data set in a grid.
Class.rdfs:label: matrix chart

Class.terms:description: A network diagram consists of a set of vertices connected by edges.
Class.rdfs:label: network diagram

Class.terms:description: A block histogram contains an x-axis that is divided into bins which correspond to value ranges. Each item in the data set is drawn as a rectangular block, and the blocks are piled into the bins to show how many values in each range.
Class.rdfs:label: block histogram

Class.terms:description: A bubble chart contains circles whose area corresponds to a value.
Class.rdfs:label: bubble chart

Class.terms:description: A stack graph is a statistical graph which presents multiple series in which the distance between one series and another indicates the relative contribution to the total for any x-value.
Class.rdfs:label: stack graph

Class.terms:description: A treemap is a chart that fully partitions the area into a set of rectangles whose area represents its relative value.
Class.rdfs:label: treemap

Class.terms:description: A word tree is a chart that links phrases with contexts through a tree-like branching structure.
Class.rdfs:label: word tree

Class.terms:description: A textual chart is a chart containing text.
Class.rdfs:label: textual chart

Class.terms:description: A tag cloud is a visualization of word frequencies.
Class.rdfs:label: tag cloud

Class.terms:description: A phrase net diagram illustrates the relationship between different words used in a text.
Class.rdfs:label: phrase net diagram

Class.terms:description: A mereological chart is a chart that illustrates the parts in the context of the whole.
Class.rdfs:label: mereological chart

Class.terms:description: A numeric label is a number used as a label.
Class.rdfs:label: numeric label

Class.terms:description: A start position is the proximal position of an object relative to an origin in a linear system.
Class.rdfs:label: start position

Class.terms:description: An interval is a set of real numbers that includes all numbers between any two numbers in the set.
Class.rdfs:label: interval

Class.terms:description: A tree diagram is a hierarchical network diagram in which a root vertex is connected to one or more other vertices through a directed edge, which in turn may be connected to other vertices.
Class.rdfs:label: tree diagram

Class.terms:description: A flowchart is a diagram that represents an algorithm or process, showing the steps as boxes of various kinds, and their order by connecting these with arrows.
Class.rdfs:label: flowchart

Class.terms:description: A Venn diagram is a chart that illustrates all possible logical relations between a finite collection of sets as overlapping circles.
Class.rdfs:label: venn diagram

Class.terms:description: A dendrogram is a tree diagram used to illustrate the arrangement of the clusters produced by hierarchical clustering.
Class.rdfs:label: dendrogram

Class.terms:description: A default parameter is a parameter which has a default value.
Class.rdfs:label: default parameter

Class.terms:description: An end position is the distal position of an object relative to an origin in a linear system.
Class.rdfs:label: end position

Class.terms:description: A standard operating procedure is a specification approved for use in specific environments.
Class.rdfs:label: standard operating procedure

Class.terms:description: A syllable is a verbal entity of language having one vowel sound, with or without surrounding consonants, forming the whole or a part of a word.
Class.rdfs:label: syllable

Class.terms:description: A consonant is a verbal entity of language that is articulated with complete or partial closure of the vocal tract.
Class.rdfs:label: consonant

Class.terms:description: A vowel is a verbal entity of language that is pronounced with an open vocal tract so that there is no build-up of air pressure at any point above the glottis.
Class.rdfs:label: vowel

Class.terms:description: A sign language (also signed language) is a language that involves manual communication and body language to convey meaning. This can involve simultaneously combining hand shapes, orientation and movement of the hands, arms or body, and facial expressions to fluidly express a speaker's thoughts.
Class.rdfs:label: sign language

Class.terms:description: A verbal language is a language that uses sounds to communicate.
Class.rdfs:label: verbal language

Class.terms:description: written language is a language that is communicated through a writing system.
Class.rdfs:label: written language

Class.terms:description: A gene-disease association is an association between a gene and a disease.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association

Class.terms:description: A chemical-disease association is an association between a chemical and a disease.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical-disease association

Class.terms:description: A diagnostic opinion is an opinion resulting from a medical diagnostic procedure.
Class.rdfs:label: diagnostic opinion

Class.terms:description: An opinion is a belief that is the result of emotion or interpretation of facts.
Class.rdfs:label: opinion

Class.terms:description: age is the length of time that a person has lived or a thing has existed.
Class.rdfs:label: age

Class.terms:description: An ethnic group is a group of people whose members identify with each other through a common heritage, consisting of a common culture, including a shared language or dialect.
Class.rdfs:label: ethnic group

Class.terms:description: A syndrome is composed of a set of several clinically recognizable features, signs (observed by someone other than the patient), symptoms (reported by the patient), phenomena or characteristics that often occur together.
Class.rdfs:label: syndrome

Class.terms:description: A ratio is a relationship between two numbers of the same kind expressed arithmetically as a dimensionless quotient of the two which explicitly indicates how many times the first number contains the second.
Class.rdfs:label: ratio

Class.terms:description: A dose is the quantity of a chemical substance administered to a biological system.
Class.rdfs:label: dose

Class.terms:description: effective dose is the amount of a substance required to produce an effect on a predefined percentage of a population.
Class.rdfs:label: effective dose

Class.terms:description: An expected value (or e-value) is the weighted average of all possible values that a random variable can take on.
Class.rdfs:label: expected value

Class.terms:description: A prognosis is a proposition about the likely course of a disease, the chance of recovery or recurrence.
Class.rdfs:label: prognosis

Class.terms:description: A report is a textual document made that present focused, salient content to a specific audience.
Class.rdfs:label: report

Class.terms:description: A medical health record is a record of a single patient's medical history.
Class.rdfs:label: medical health record

Class.terms:description: A medical report is a report prepared by a health care practioner about test outcomes or health status of an individual.
Class.rdfs:label: medical report

Class.terms:description: A peer reviewed article is an article that has undergone peer-review and deemed acceptable for publication.
Class.rdfs:label: peer reviewed article

Class.terms:description: A major version number is a version of a software that exhibits a significant change in functionalilty from a prior version.
Class.rdfs:label: major version number

Class.terms:description: A minor version number is a version of a software that exhibits minor features or significant fix from a prior version.
Class.rdfs:label: minor version number

Class.terms:description: A revision number is a version of a software in which bugs have been fixed from a prior version.
Class.rdfs:label: revision number

Class.terms:description: A morpheme is the smallest semantically meaningful unit in a language.
Class.rdfs:label: morpheme

Class.terms:description: A study design is a protocol for the proper execution of a study which normally requires a carefullly crafted research question or hypothesis and at least one variable under observation and observed values for that variable.
Class.rdfs:label: study design

Class.terms:description: A recipe is a set of instructions that describe how to prepare or make something.
Class.rdfs:label: recipe

Class.terms:description: An experimental protocol is an action specification with respect to the design and implementation of experiments. In addition to providing a detailed set of procedures and lists of required equipment and instruments, experimental protocols often include information on safety precautions, the calculation of results and reporting standards, including statistical analysis and rules for predefining and documenting excluded data to avoid bias.
Class.rdfs:label: experimental protocol

Class.terms:description: A reason is a justification that specifies the motive for an action or a determination.
Class.rdfs:label: reason

Class.terms:description: The ordinal position of a character in a sequence of characters.
Class.rdfs:label: character position

Class.terms:description: The position of the first character in a word as an offset from the first character of the text in which it is found.
Class.rdfs:label: word start position

Class.terms:description: word end position is the position of the last character in a word as an offset from the first character of the text in which it is found.
Class.rdfs:label: word end position

Class.terms:description: A population is all the organisms that both belong to the same group or species and live in the same geographical area.
Class.rdfs:label: population

Class.terms:description: A human population refers to a collection of human beings.
Class.rdfs:label: human population

Class.terms:description: A group of people affiliated by consanguinity, affinity, or co-residence.
Class.rdfs:label: family

Class.terms:description: A community is a sizeable social unit that shares common values.
Class.rdfs:label: community

Class.terms:description: speculation is an opinion based on incomplete evidence.
Class.rdfs:label: speculation

Class.terms:description: A control group is a group of individuals that are not subject to an intervention of interest, but rather serve as a baseline to compare the outcomes in the intervention group.
Class.rdfs:label: control group

Class.terms:description: An intervention group is a group of individuals that are subject to an intervention.
Class.rdfs:label: intervention group

Class.terms:description: A control variable that is believed to alter the dependent or independent variables, but may not actually be the focus of the experiment. So that variable will be kept constant or monitored to try to minimise its effect on the experiment.
Class.rdfs:label: control variable

Class.terms:description: text span start position is the position (offset) of the first character of a text span in relation the text it is from.
Class.rdfs:label: text span start position

Class.terms:description: text span end position is the position (offset) of the last character of a text span in relation the text it is from.
Class.rdfs:label: text span end position

Class.terms:description: A text span is a subset of contiguous sequence of characters of a textual entity.
Class.rdfs:label: text span

Class.terms:description: A t-statistic is a ratio of the departure of an estimated parameter from its notional value and its standard error.
Class.rdfs:label: t-statistic

Class.terms:description: A microarray probe set identifier is an identifier for a set of probe pairs selected to represent expressed sequences on an array.
Class.rdfs:label: microarray probe set identifier

Class.terms:description: A gene expression value is a measured value obtained from a gene expression experiment.
Class.rdfs:label: gene expression value

Class.terms:description: A differential gene expression ratio is the ratio of gene expression values from a test sample compared to a control sample.
Class.rdfs:label: differential gene expression ratio

Class.terms:description: A genotype is a functional specification of a biological entity in terms of its genetic composition (or lack thereof).
Class.rdfs:label: genotype

Class.terms:description: A vocabulary is a collection of terms.
Class.rdfs:label: vocabulary

Class.terms:description: A t-statistic based increased differential gene expression is a differential gene expression ratio in which the t-statistic is greater than zero.
Class.rdfs:label: t-statistic based increased differential gene expression

Class.terms:description: A t-statistic based decreased differential gene expression is a differential gene expression ratio in which the t-statistic is less than zero.
Class.rdfs:label: t-statistic based decreased differential gene expression

Class.terms:description: A date of database submission refers to the moment in time in which some information was submitted/received to a database system.
Class.rdfs:label: date of database submission

Class.terms:description: concentration is the amount of substance per unit volume of a solution
Class.rdfs:label: concentration

Class.terms:description: pH is a measure of the activity of the (solvated) hydrogen ion.
