Class.schema:comment: pH is defined as the decimal logarithm of the reciprocal of the hydrogen ion activity, aH+, in a solution.
Class.rdfs:label: pH

Class.terms:description: electronic structure is the electron configuration is the distribution of electrons of an atom or molecule (or other physical structure) in atomic or molecular orbitals.
Class.resource:example: the electron configuration of the neon atom is 1s2 2s2 2p6.
Class.rdfs:label: electronic structure

Class.terms:description: A crystal structure is the arrangement of atoms or molecules in a crystalline liquid or solid.
Class.rdfs:label: crystal structure

Class.terms:description: A pathway is an effective specification that outlines a set of actions that forms a way to achieve an objective.
Class.rdfs:label: pathway

Class.terms:description: A central tendency measure is a central value or a typical value for a probability distribution.
Class.rdfs:label: centrality measure

Class.terms:description: A mean is the central tendency of a collection of numbers taken as the sum of the numbers divided by the size of the collection.
Class.rdfs:label: mean

Class.terms:description: A median is the numerical value separating the higher half of a sample, a population, or a probability distribution, from the lower half.
Class.rdfs:label: median

Class.terms:description: A mode is the value that appears most often in a set of data.
Class.rdfs:label: mode

Class.terms:description: A sum is the result of adding a set of values together.
Class.rdfs:label: sum

Class.terms:description: A minimal value is smallest value of an attribute for the entities in the defined set.
Class.rdfs:label: minimal value

Class.terms:description: A maximal value is largest value of an attribute for the entities in the defined set.
Class.rdfs:label: maximal value

Class.terms:description: A count of the instances of a class or members in a collection.
Class.rdfs:label: member count

Class.terms:description: A union is a list of all of the values of an attribute for the entities in the defined set.
Class.rdfs:label: union

Class.terms:description: An intersection is a list of only the values of an attribute for the entities in the defined set where all entities have that value.
Class.rdfs:label: intersection

Class.terms:description: A sequence is an ordered list of entities. Like a set, it contains members (also called elements, or terms).
Class.resource:example: For example, (M, A, R, Y) is a sequence of letters that differs from (A, R, M, Y), as the ordering matters, and (1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8), which contains the number 1 at two different positions, is a valid sequence.
Class.rdfs:label: sequence

Class.terms:description: A gene-variant disease association in which a mutation in the gene/protein results in the development or maintenance of the disease.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with causal mutation

Class.terms:description: A gene disease association in which the gene is a therapeutic marker for the disease.
Class.resource:hasSynonym: gene-disease association arising from a therapeutic role of the gene/protein
Class.rdfs:label: therapeutic gene-disease association

Class.terms:description: A gene-disease association in which the gene/protein is involved in the etiology or maintenance of the disease.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease biomarker association

Class.terms:description: A gene-disease association in which a sequence variation (a mutation, a SNP) is associated with the disease.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with genetic variation

Class.terms:description: A gene-disease association in which the disease phenotype is associated with an altered expression of the gene.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with altered gene expression

Class.terms:description: A gene-disease association in which the disease phenotype is associated with post-translational modifications in the protein product.
Class.resource:example: methylation or phosphorylation of protein product
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with post-translational modification

Class.terms:description: number of objects produced is a count of objects that were produced in some process.
Class.rdfs:label: number of objects produced

Class.terms:description: number of objects consumed is a count of objects that were consumed in some process.
Class.rdfs:label: number of objects consumed

Class.terms:description: A difference in number of objects produced is a count of the number of objects produced with respect to a second variable (space, time, etc)
Class.rdfs:label: difference in number of objects produced

Class.terms:description: An increase in the number of objects produced is the positive value of a difference in number of objects produced.
Class.rdfs:label: increase in number of objects produced

Class.terms:description: An decrease in the number of objects produced is the negative value of a difference in number of objects produced.
Class.rdfs:label: decrease in number of objects produced

Class.terms:description: user account allows a user to authenticate to system services and be granted authorization to access them.
Class.rdfs:label: user account

Class.terms:description: An annotation is a written explanatory or critical description, or other in-context information (e.g., pattern, motif, link), that has been associated with data or other types of information.
Class.rdfs:label: annotation

Class.terms:description: A comment is a verbal or written remark often related to an added piece of information, or an observation or statement.
Class.rdfs:label: comment

Class.terms:description: An audio recording is an electrical or mechanical inscription and re-creation of sound waves, such as spoken voice, singing, instrumental music, or sound effects.
Class.rdfs:label: audio recording

Class.terms:description: An issue is a single instance of a periodically published journal, magazine, or newspaper.
Class.rdfs:label: issue

Class.terms:description: A slideshow is a visual presentation of information contained within a collection of slides.
Class.rdfs:label: slideshow

Class.terms:description: A database cross-reference is an association between one data item and another.
Class.rdfs:label: database cross-reference

Class.terms:description: An exact cross-reference is a database cross-reference in which one entity is equivalent to the other based on all the entitie's attributes (minus the source).
Class.rdfs:label: exact cross-reference

Class.terms:description: A statement is a proposition that is either (a) a meaningful declarative sentence that is either true or false, or (b) that which a true or false declarative sentence asserts.
Class.rdfs:label: statement

Class.terms:description: A slope or gradient of a line describes its steepness, incline, or grade. A higher slope value indicates a steeper incline. Slope is normally described by the ratio of the "rise" divided by the "run" between two points on a line.
Class.rdfs:label: slope

Class.terms:description: A software process identifier is an identifier for a software process in some operating system.
Class.rdfs:label: software process identifier

Class.terms:description: A database row is a row that is part of a database table.
Class.rdfs:label: database row

Class.terms:description: a SADI semantic web service is a semantic web service that follows the SADI specification
Class.rdfs:label: SADI semantic web service

Class.terms:description: a semantic web service is a web service that provides a formal, machine understanble description of its functionality.
Class.rdfs:label: semantic web service

Class.terms:description: a REST web service is a web service that provides functionality according to the Representational State Transfer (REST) specification.
Class.rdfs:label: REST web service

Class.terms:description: a SOAP web service is a web service that implements Simple Object Access Protocol (SOAP).
Class.rdfs:label: SOAP web service

Class.terms:description: media are audo/visual/audiovisual modes of communicating information for mass consumption.
Class.rdfs:label: media

Class.terms:description: history is a sequence of past events.
Class.rdfs:label: history

Class.terms:description: A structural motif is a pattern in a structure formed by a spatial arrangement of objects (e.g. atoms).
Class.rdfs:label: structural motif

Class.terms:description: A catalog is a systemic collection of items of the same type.
Class.rdfs:label: catalog

Class.terms:description: Likelihood is the hypothetical probability that an event that has already occurred would yield a specific outcome.
Class.rdfs:label: likelihood

Class.terms:description: Log likelihood is the natural logarithm of the likelihood function
Class.rdfs:label: log likelihood

Class.terms:description: A standard score is the (signed) number of standard deviations an observation or datum is above the mean.
Class.resource:hasSynonym: z-value, z-score, normal score, standardadized variable.
Class.rdfs:label: standard score

Class.terms:description: an interval is a set of real numbers with the property that any number that lies between thwo numbers in the set is also included in the set.
Class.resource:example: The set of all numbers x satisfying 0<=x<=1 is an interval which contains 0 and 1, as well as numbers between them.
Class.rdfs:label: interval

Class.terms:description: an open interval is an interval that does not include its endpoints.
Class.resource:example: (0,1) is an open interval that is greater than 0 and less than 1.
Class.rdfs:label: open interval

Class.terms:description: A closed interval is an interval that includes its endpoints, and is denoted with square brackets.
Class.resource:example: [0,1] is a closed interval that is greater than or equal to 0 and less than or equal to 1.
Class.rdfs:label: closed interval

Class.terms:description: a chemical-pathway association is an association between a chemical and a pathway.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical-pathway association

Class.terms:description: a left open interval is an interval in which there is no element that is smaller than all other elements.
Class.rdfs:label: left open interval

Class.terms:description: a right open interval is an interval in which there is no element that is greater than all other elements.
Class.rdfs:label: right open interval

Class.terms:description: a right closed interval is an interval in which there is a real number that is larger than all of its elements.
Class.rdfs:label: right closed interval

Class.terms:description: a left closed interval is an interval in which there is a real number that is smaller than all its elements.
Class.rdfs:label: left closed interval

Class.terms:description: a pharmacokinetic pathway is a metabolic pathway which describes the metabolism of a drug molecule.
Class.rdfs:label: pharmacokinetic pathway

Class.terms:description: a pharmacodynamic pathay is a regulatory pathway in which a drug molecule regulates the activity of one or more components organized in a pathway.
Class.rdfs:label: pharmacodynamic pathway

Class.terms:description: a chemical-gene assocation is an assocation between a chemical and a gene.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical-gene assocation

Class.terms:description: set item is an item in a set.
Class.rdfs:label: set item

Class.terms:description: a collection item is an item in a collection.
Class.rdfs:label: collection item

Class.terms:description: a list item is an item in a list.
Class.rdfs:label: list item

Class.terms:description: an ordered list item is an item in an ordered list.
Class.rdfs:label: ordered list item

Class.terms:description: An ovopub is an information content entity that contains and links to one or more resources and/or statements, including those describing its provenance, and is itself a dereferenceable resource.
Class.rdfs:label: ovopub

Class.terms:description: A collection ovopub is an ovopub that contains and links to one or more assertion subgraphs and/or ovopubs, as well as statements describing its provenance. It is used to share a specific set of items or restrict a search to the resources contained therein.
Class.rdfs:label: collection ovopub

Class.terms:description: An assertion ovopub is an ovopub that contains and links to an assertion subgraph with one or more statements that may be true or false, as well as statements describing its provenance.
Class.rdfs:label: assertion ovopub

Class.terms:description: the date at which an information content entity was made public.
Class.rdfs:label: date of issue

Class.terms:description: an ordered list of authors.
Class.rdfs:label: author list

Class.terms:description: an ordered list is a list in which items are sequentially ordered.
Class.rdfs:label: ordered list

Class.terms:description: a middle name is a name assigned to an individual that is not the first or last name.
Class.rdfs:label: middle name

Class.terms:description: a middle initial is an abbreviated middle name.
Class.rdfs:label: middle initial

Class.terms:description: a telephone number is an identifier used to connect to a physical device capable of transfering voice or data over a network.
Class.rdfs:label: telephone number

Class.terms:description: a cellular phone number is a number to connect to a mobile device
Class.rdfs:label: cellular phone number

Class.terms:description: a fax number is a number to connect to fax device
Class.rdfs:label: fax number

Class.terms:description: an IP number is an number to connect to a device on the internet.
Class.rdfs:label: IP number

Class.terms:description: an email address is an identifier to send mail to particular electronic mailbox.
Class.rdfs:label: email address

Class.terms:description: a work phone number is the number to connect to an phone at a place of work.
Class.rdfs:label: work phone number

Class.terms:description: a home phone number is the number to connect to an phone at a place of residence.
Class.rdfs:label: home phone number

Class.terms:description: A protein expression value is a quantity obtained from a protein expression experiment.
Class.rdfs:label: protein expression value

Class.terms:description: copy number variation refers to the number of deletions/duplications of a DNA region as compared to some reference state.
Class.rdfs:label: copy number variation

Class.terms:description: metadata is data that provides information about data.
Class.rdfs:label: metadata

Class.terms:description: A diagnosis is the result of a medical investigation to identify a disorder from its signs and symptoms.
Class.rdfs:label: diagnosis

Class.terms:description: a directed acyclic graph or DAG is a network digram that contains directed edges in which nodes may have multiple parents, but there are no cycles.
Class.rdfs:label: directed acyclic graph

Class.terms:description: an arc is a closed segment of a differentiable curve.
Class.rdfs:label: arc

Class.terms:description: an edge is a line connecting two graph vertices.
Class.rdfs:label: edge

Class.terms:description: a node or vertex is a point in a graph.
Class.rdfs:label: node

Class.terms:description: A gene-disease association in which a gene mutation is known to modify the clinical presentation of the disease.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with modifying mutation

Class.terms:description: A gene-disease association in which a germline mutation in the gene predisposes to the development of the disease, and it is necessary but not sufficient for the manifestation of the disease.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with susceptibility mutation

Class.terms:description: A gene-variant disease association in which a germline mutation in the gene/protein results in the development or maintenance of the disease, and it may be passed on to offspring.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with germline causal mutation

Class.terms:description: A gene-variant disease association in which a somatic mutation in the gene/protein results in the development or maintenance of the disease, and it may not be passed on to offspring.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with somatic causal mutation

Class.terms:description: A gene-variant disease association in which a somatic mutation in the gene modifies the clinical presentation of the disease, and it may not be passed on to offspring.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with somatic modifying mutation

Class.terms:description: A gene-variant disease association in which a germline mutation in the gene modifies the clinical presentation of the disease, and it may be passed on to offspring.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with germline modifying mutation

Class.terms:description: A gene-disease association in which the fusion between two different genes (promotor and/or other coding DNA regions) is associated with the disease.
Class.rdfs:label: fusion gene-disease association

Class.terms:description: A gene-disease association in which the gene is included in a chromosomal rearrangement associated with a particular manifestation of the disease.
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with chromosomal rearrangement

Class.terms:description: a gene-disease association that is linked with some genomic alteration
Class.rdfs:label: gene-disease association linked with genomic alterations

Class.terms:description:
DisGeNET Disease specificity is a measure of disease coverage. It is calculated from the negative base 2 log of the ratio of number of diseases associated to the total number of diseases.
The measure is described here: http://www.disgenet.org/web/DisGeNET/menu/dbinfo#specificity
Class.rdfs:label: DisGeNET disease specificity

Class.terms:description:
The DisGeNET pleiotropy index is a measure of specificity as it pertains to classes of disease. The disease pleotropy index is computed from the ratio of the number of disease classes associated with an entity over the total number of disease classes multplied by 100.
The measure is defined here: http://www.disgenet.org/web/DisGeNET/menu/dbinfo#pleiotropy
Class.rdfs:label: DisGeNET Pleiotropy Index

Class.terms:description: A week is a period of 7 consecutive days.
Class.rdfs:label: week

Class.terms:description: Specific gravity is the ratio of the density of a substance to the density of a reference substance; equivalently, it is the ratio of the mass of a substance to the mass of a reference substance for the same given volume.
Class.rdfs:label: specific gravity

Class.terms:description: The amount of change accumulated per unit time.
Class.rdfs:label: rate of change

Class.terms:description: Frequency is the number of occurrences of a repeating event per unit time
Class.rdfs:label: frequency

Class.terms:description: Speed is the rate of change of an object's position.
Class.rdfs:label: speed

Class.terms:description: The rate of change of an object's position and the direction of that change
Class.rdfs:label: velocity

Class.terms:description: A slide is an visual representation meant to communicate some information.
Class.rdfs:label: slide

Class.terms:description: A statute is a formal written enactment of a legislative authority that governs a state, city or country.
Class.rdfs:label: statute

Class.terms:description: A legal document proposing or enacting a law or a group of laws.
Class.rdfs:label: legislation

Class.terms:description: A legal document is a formally executed written document that can be formally attributed to its author, records and formally expresses a legally enforceable act, process, or contractual duty, obligation, or right, and therefore evidences that act, process, or agreement.
Class.rdfs:label: legal document

Class.terms:description: A brief is a written legal document used in various legal adversarial systems that is presented to a court arguing why one party to a particular case should prevail.
Class.rdfs:label: brief

Class.terms:description: A bill is proposed legislation under consideration by a legislature.
Class.rdfs:label: bill

Class.terms:description: a versioned dataset is a dataset with a particular release date or release number.
Class.rdfs:label: versioned dataset

Class.dc:description: a protein family is a collection of proteins that share a common evolutionary origin, reflected by their related function and similarity in composition or structure.
Class.rdfs:label: protein family

Class.dc:description: a unigene cluster is a collection of transcripts (ESTs and mRNAs) that map to a particular genomic region.
Class.rdfs:label: unigene cluster

Class.dc:description: a gene symbol is a short name assigned to a gene.
Class.rdfs:label: gene symbol

Class.dc:description: a statement of consequence is a statement concerning the result or effect of an action or condition.
Class.rdfs:label: statement of consequence

Class.dc:description: a notation is a series or system of written symbols used to represent numbers, amounts, or elements.
Class.rdfs:label: notation

Class.dc:description: a notation to describe a chemical entity
Class.rdfs:label: chemical notation

Class.dc:description: The HGVS (human genome variation society) notation is a notation to specify a sequence variation in dna, rna, proteins, and other biomolecules.
Class.rdfs:label: hgvs notation

Class.dc:description: an ontology is a formal specification of entities, their attributes and relationships.
Class.rdfs:label: ontology

Class.dc:description: evidence is the body of facts or information indicating whether a belief or proposition is true or valid.
Class.rdfs:label: evidence

Class.dc:description: A terminology is a set of terms used for a specified application.
Class.rdfs:label: terminology

Class.terms:description: Density (volumetric mass density) is the quantity of mass per unit volume of a substance.
Class.rdfs:label: density

Class.terms:description: The surface area of a is a measure of the total area that the surface of the object occupies.
Class.rdfs:label: surface area

Class.terms:description: The aspect ratio of a geometric shape is the ratio of its sizes in different dimensions.
Class.rdfs:label: aspect ratio

Class.terms:description: biological data is scientific data relevant to biology.
Class.rdfs:label: biological data

Class.terms:description: genetic data is data pertaining to genetics.
Class.rdfs:label: genetic data

Class.terms:description: A PDB chain identifier is a alphabetical label to identify a molecule in a structure provided by the Protein DataBank .
Class.rdfs:label: PDB chain identifier

Class.terms:description: A PDB record identifier is an identifier for a PDB generated record.
Class.rdfs:label: PDB record identifier

Class.terms:description: evolutionary lineage is a sequence of species, that form a line of descent, each new species the direct result of speciation from an immediate ancestral species.
Class.rdfs:label: evolutionary lineage

Class.terms:description: family history is the systematic narrative and research of past events relating to a specific family, or specific families.
Class.rdfs:label: family history

Class.terms:description: generation number is a count of the number of biological reproduction events elapsed from some starting reference point.
Class.rdfs:label: generation number

Class.terms:description: bioinformatic data is data genereated or used for computer-based investigations of biological phenomena.
Class.rdfs:label: bioinformatic data

Class.terms:description: A sequence alignment is the character-based alignment of sequences using some method.
Class.rdfs:label: sequence alignment

Class.terms:description: A multiple sequence alignment is a sequence alignment involving more than two sequences.
Class.rdfs:label: multiple sequence alignment

Class.terms:description: A pairwise sequence alignment is the alignment of exactly 2 sequences.
Class.rdfs:label: pairwise sequence alignment

Class.terms:description: medical data is data of interest to medicine.
Class.rdfs:label: medical data

Class.terms:description: A drug regulatory authority is a regulatory authority which acts to control what substances may be used to treat individuals.
Class.rdfs:label: drug regulatory authority

Class.terms:description: A biochemical pathway specifies a series of biochemical modifications and transformations towards achieving some biological outcome.
Class.rdfs:label: biochemical pathway

Class.terms:description: A chemical reaction pathway specifies a series of chemical reactions towards producing some chemical product.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical reaction pathway

Class.terms:description: A chemical synthesis pathway is a pathway involved in the assembly of a chemical.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical synthesis pathway

Class.terms:description: A chemical degradation pathway is a pathway involved in the disassembly of a chemical.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical degradation pathway

Class.terms:description: A sequence profile is provides the preference for a character at each position of an abstracted sequence.
Class.rdfs:label: sequence profile

Class.terms:description: A metabolic pathway is a series of biochemical reactions that begins with one or more substrates and ends with one or more products.
Class.rdfs:label: metabolic pathway

Class.terms:description: A regulatory pathway is a series of biochemical reactions that lead to the increase or decrease of activity of participating molecular components.
Class.rdfs:label: regulatory pathway

Class.terms:description: A medical history is a record of the events of a recipient of medical care.
Class.rdfs:label: medical history

Class.terms:description: A molecular structure file is a file that contains a description of molecular structure.
Class.rdfs:label: molecular structure file

Class.terms:description: A chemical datum is a scientific data item which conforms to some specification, either for how it is calculated or for how it is measured, and is commonly used in the domain of chemistry to name and differentiate different numeric properties (both calculated and measured) which are about chemical entities.
Class.rdfs:label: chemical data

Class.terms:description: A PDB file is a molecular structure file specified by the Protein DataBank (PDB).
Class.rdfs:label: PDB file

Class.terms:description: A collection of 3D molecular structure models is just that.
Class.rdfs:label: collection of 3d molecular structure models
